---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Editorial Team | wrongfuldeathcalc.com';
const description = 'Meet the editorial team behind wrongfuldeathcalc.com — credentials, areas of focus, and our editorial review process.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Editorial Team</h1>
  <p>wrongfuldeathcalc.com is reviewed by a small editorial team with professional experience in wrongful death and probate practice. We are not attorneys; we do not represent clients. We read the state statutes, treatises, and verdict reporters so our content reflects how the practice actually works rather than how it's marketed.</p>

  <h2>Wrongful Death Practice</h2>
  <p><strong>Credentials:</strong> Paralegals in wrongful death litigation, with prior support work on plaintiff-side cases including motor vehicle fatalities, workplace fatalities, and product-liability deaths, and familiarity with forensic-economics methodology and damage modeling.</p>
  <p><strong>Coverage areas:</strong> state wrongful death statutes; statutory beneficiary structures; economic and non-economic damages frameworks; survival actions versus wrongful death actions; statute of limitations analysis; coordination between wrongful death claims and probate proceedings.</p>
  <p><strong>Editorial role:</strong> reviews every published page, signs off on methodology, approves changes to calculator formulas and multipliers.</p>

  <h2>Survivor and Estate Damages</h2>
  <p><strong>Credentials:</strong> Paralegals in probate practice, with backgrounds in estate administration, probate court procedure, and coordination with civil litigation arising from a decedent's death.</p>
  <p><strong>Coverage areas:</strong> probate procedure as it intersects with wrongful death recovery; estate appointment and personal representative procedure; survival action distinct from wrongful death action; allocation of recovery among statutory beneficiaries; the role of life insurance and pension benefits in damages analysis.</p>
  <p><strong>Editorial role:</strong> drafts survivor-damages content; reviews probate-related portions of guides; flags state-specific allocation rules.</p>

  <h2>Editorial process</h2>
  <p>Pages move through draft &rarr; technical review &rarr; editorial review &rarr; publication. Technical review checks the math, the cited statutes, and any state-specific claims. Editorial review checks clarity, structure, and that the page is useful to its intended reader (a survivor in the days or weeks after a death, not a law student or attorney). Pages are dated; substantive updates are flagged with a revision note.</p>
  <p>Send corrections through the <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>. We respond and update the page with a correction note when the issue is substantive.</p>

  <h2>What we don't do</h2>
  <p>We don't provide legal advice on specific cases. We don't refer cases to attorneys for compensation. We don't take a cut of settlements. We don't sell visitor information. Revenue comes from display advertising via Google AdSense.</p>
  <p>For specific legal advice in your situation, find a wrongful death attorney licensed in your state. Your state bar's lawyer referral service is a good starting point; the American Association for Justice and state trial lawyer associations also maintain referral resources for wrongful death.</p>
</BaseLayout>
